observations.recommendation:
The Inventory Committee prepare and submit the copy of RPCPPE to the Auditor in the prescribed format, not later than January 31 of each year;

The Inventory Committee ensure that RPCPPE reflects comprehensively and cumulatively the PPE of the LGU as of the date of the conduct of physical count;

In the preparation of the RPCPPE, the Inventory Committee ensure to follow the prescribed format, properly and completely filled out all the required columns, and check the entries therein to avoid redundancy; and

The Municipal Accounting Office (MAccO) and Inventory Committee reconcile the difference between the PPE balances recorded in the books and in the RPCPPE.

Adjust the initial entries made in the “Due to GSIS” account for those non-GSIS-related transactions; 

Strictly adhere to the proper usage of account titles and the corresponding posting thereof in the appropriate SLs to ensure that only relevant transactions are posted in the ledger in accordance with the descriptions and instructions provided in Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009; and

Ensure full compliance with the provisions of Section 69 of PD No. 1445, Sections 5 and 6(b) of RA No. 8291 of The Government Service Insurance System Act of 1977 dated May 30, 1997.

The MAccO prioritize and continue to reconstruct/update its PPE ledger cards (PPELCs);

Based on the data in the PPELCs, MAccO evaluate each item of PPE to determine whether the new capitalization threshold of ₱50,000.00 shall be applied individually or in aggregate (such as in the case of Information and Communication Technology Equipment). After such evaluation, determine the total amount of tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 (as well as those below ₱15,000.00) which can be derecognized from the books;

Before any derecognition, the General Services Officer/Property and Supply Officer-Designate ensure that:

i. Tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts below ₱15,000.00 were completely documented by previously issued Inventory Custodian Slips (ICSs);

ii. Tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 were completely documented by previously issued Property Acknowledgment Receipts (PARs) (or currently issued ICSs, when the previously issued PARs were replaced by ICSs at the discretion of the LGU); and

Secure the preparation of the registry of semi-Expendable Property Issued (RegSPI) for each class of semi-expendable property (low-valued items and high-value items) by fund.

Prospectively, the GSO/Property and Supply Officer-Designate secure and maintain the following:

i. The ICSs of the tangible items acquired and issued prior to CY 2022 with amounts from ₱15,000.00 to below ₱50,000.00 (as well as those below ₱15,000.00) which were derecognized from the books;

ii. The ICSs of tangible items which meet the definition and recognition criteria of PPE but cost is below ₱50,000.00 semi-expendable property) acquired during CY 2022 and onwards;

iii. The PARs of tangible items acquired during CY 2022 and onwards recognized as PPE; and

iv. The RegSPI for each class of semi-expendable property (low-valued items and high-value items) by fund.

The LCE consider the formulation or adoption of internal policy governing the monetization of leave credits aligned with existing relevant rules and regulations such as, but not limited to, the Omnibus Rules on Leave as amended and Circular No. 2012-001. Further, said internal policy should be communicated to all the Offices of the LGU to endeavor uniformity;

As an additional control measure, ensure coordination of the Human Resources Management Officer with the LCE on the allowed number of days that a requesting employee may be allowed to monetize subject to the provisions of Sections 22 and 23 of the Omnibus Rules as amended before the approval of the Request for Monetization; and

The Municipal Accountant ensure that only the claims for monetization of leave credits with complete supporting documents subject to the provision of Item 5.14 of COA Circular No. 2012-001 should be paid.

Require the Municipal Engineer’s Office to provide the concerned offices, the designated Property and Supply Officer, Inventory Committee, and MAccO of available records pertaining to local road networks with complete description and cost segregation to enable reconciliation of respective existing records and, prospectively, to facilitate the preparation of required reports and records in the format prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008;

Direct the designated Property and Supply Officer to prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components, including Road Map. Moreover, ensure that the Report on Local Road Network be prepared by the designated Property and Supply Officer at the end of accounting period; 

Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of its road networks in order to ascertain the existence of the balance of the account Road Networks;

Reconcile the reports and records of designated Property and Supply Officer and Inventory Committee with the MAccO to ensure the fair presentation of the Road Networks account in the financial statement; and

Adequately provide the required disclosure pertaining to Road Networks in the Notes to financial statement.

Document the request for write-off for account balances which were considered dormant and where collectability could no longer be ascertained pursuant to COA Circular No. 2016-005; 

The Municipal Mayor file request for authority to write-off dormant receivable accounts; and

Substantiate the undocumented receivable balances for proper action.

Recommendations:
a. Municipal accountant (i) maintains property ledger cards for each class of PPE, and (ii) updates all subsidiary ledger cards and ensures that they contain complete details/description of the property to facilitate proper reconciliation with the RCPPE and RPCLRN;
Please refer to AAPSI_2024-04a folder, for your reference.
b. Municipal GSO should maintain complete property cards with complete details/information of the PPEs; ensuring that all entries include complete item property descriptions.
c. Municipal Accountant (i) transfer to the appropriate PPE accounts the cost of the completed projects; (ii) compute and recognize their corresponding depreciation; and;
d. Municipal Engineer must ensure to furnish the Accounting Office copies of the certificate of completion to facilitate the reclassification of completed projects from CIP to their appropriate PPE accounts.

Recommendations:
a. Inventory Committee to conduct the physical count of all supplies and materials and then reconcile the results of the count with available records in the Accounting and General Services Offices and submit to the Audit team the RPCI and SSMI;
b. Municipal Accountant should coordinate with concerned departments for the timely submission of reports;
c. Institute measures to ensure the timely conduct of annual physical inventory and submission of the corresponding report.

Recommendations:
a. Municipal Accountant to: (i) reconcile records of the Due to BIR, GSIS, Pag-IBIG, and PhilHealth accounts as regards unremitted and unidentified PYs’ transactions; (ii) adjust the books; accordingly, and (iii) submit to the Audit Team the supporting documents for CY 2024 adjustments and corrections;
b. Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Treasurer ensure that funds collected by the municipal government on behalf of other government agencies are remitted intact and within the prescribed due dates to avoid incurrence of interests and penalties.

Recommendations:
We recommended that the:
a. Municipal Accountant to reconstruct the SLs for all transfers of unexpended DRRMF to the STF by year of transfer and record the necessary adjustments in the books to reflect the correct balance of the Trust Liabilities-DRRMF account;

Recommendations:
We recommended to the Municipal Mayor and the E-Trike Officer the following:
a. Enter into a Contract Agreement with the Prospective New Owners (PNOs), taking into consideration the requirements laid down in Item IV of the Deployment Plan;
b. Adhere to the value of the E-trikes based on the Property Transfer Report of USD10,249.00 or ₱533,224.72 at the time of its turnover to the Municipality;
c. Compel the PNOs to complete the requirements enumerated in Appendix C of the Deployment Plan to erase any doubt on the regularity of their selection;
d. Register the E-trikes with the LTO under the name of the Municipality to easily facilitate the transfer of ownership to the PNOs;
e. Construct the four charging stations with sufficient number of socket outlets in accordance with the proposal in the Deployment Plan and designate;
f. Collect from the PNOs the charging fees and applicable penalties in case of delayed payments in accordance with Items IV(A) and IV(C) of the Deployment Plan;
g. Ensure that all properties received thru donation are properly inspected and accepted by the General Services Office and that the copy of Deed of Donation and other pertinent documents are submitted immediately to the Accounting Office for proper recording in the books;
h. Submit the document evidencing authority granted by the DOE to the LGU to utilize the five units of E-trike for official use of the Municipality and work for the immediate deployment of the remaining E-trike units; and
i. Notify DOE in writing of any non-compliance of the terms as provided for in the Deployment Plan and Deed of Donation, submit justification and request for approval of any necessary changes that should be implemented in the E- trike project.

Moving forward, we recommended that:
The LCE immediately designate/constitute an authorized Inspection Officer/Committee;
The Property and Supply Officer-Designee and the authorized Inspection Officer/Committee timely prepare and accomplish the AIR in accordance with Annex 31 and its accompanying Instructions for every procurement of goods of the LGU;
The Management, through the Property and Supply Officer-Designee and the authorized Inspection Officer/Committee, furnish the Audit Team copies of duly filled-out AIRs within 24 hours from acceptance and inspection of delivered goods; and
The Municipal Accountant ensures that claims against government funds are supported with complete documentation.

The Local Chief Executive (LCE) enjoin all department heads to comply with the provisions of this Circular;

The MAccO exert effort to create and maintain the PPE lapsing schedule, not just the depreciation schedule, to facilitate an effective and efficient monitoring of the PPE transactions; and

The MAccO prospectively effect a complete disclosure and proper presentation of the amounts and details of the PPE account in the Notes to Financial Statements in consonance with the provisions of COA Circular No. 2016-004.

Optimize the utilization of the 20 per cent DF and implement the programs, projects, and activities (PPAs) within the specified timelines to achieve the socio-economic and environmental outcomes, essential for the attainment of its goals and objectives for a desired quality of life for its constituents;

Adopt a well-defined strategy that will enhance the present monitoring and review procedures during the planning, procurement, contract implementation and program evaluation phases, to ensure proper and timely execution of the PPAs and enable immediate corrective actions for any gaps noted during the implementation; and

Make representation to Sangguniang Bayan (SB) to propose reversion of savings from 20 per cent completed projects to surplus which can be realigned to support similar programs for developmental projects that need immediate attention.

Direct the Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to strictly comply with existing laws, rules and regulations on procurement;

Direct the concerned office/s to expedite the submission of the lacking documentary requirements for evaluation of the Audit Team; and

Direct the Municipal Accountant to ensure that payment should be made only for claims supported with complete and appropriate documents.

The LCE, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant, immediately refrain from granting CAs without a legally specific purpose established and identified in the DV at the time of grant;

The BAC ensure that all purchases of materials and supplies, as well as, acquisitions of services should be undertaken in accordance with the applicable mode of procurement enumerated in the 2016 Revised Implementing Rules and Regulations (R-IRR) of RA No. 9184, moreover, should be properly and completely documented; and

Prospectively, the LCE, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant adhere strictly with the provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 prescribing the rules and regulations on granting, utilization and liquidation of CAs.

The Accounting Unit identify each transaction of CAs as to the type of account where the same should be appropriately recorded. Consequently, effect the necessary adjusting entries to correct the balances of affected accounts. Moreover, record the omitted transactions of CAs and liquidations in the appropriate accounts;

The accountable officer and the Accountant ensure the reconciliation of records in order to avoid the omission of transactions pertaining to CAs and liquidations in their respective records; and

The Accounting Unit ensure adherence with Annex B of COA Circular No. 2015-009 on the proper classification and recording of transactions in appropriate accounts.

The GAD Focal Point System (GFPS) ensure that only equally important and priority gender-responsive PPAs are incorporated in the GAD Plan and Budget;

The LCE, through GFPS, direct the concerned implementing units of GAD PPAs to ensure its full implementation at year-end; 

The GAD Monitoring and Evaluation Team of the LGU strengthen its monitoring efforts; and

Prospectively, GFPS and all concerned implementing units maximize the utilization of GAD funds.

Determine the nature of the noted variances;

Effect immediately the necessary adjusting entries to reflect the correct account balances of the RPT/SET Receivables and the corresponding Deferred RPT/SET Income accounts; and

Prospectively, ensure strict adherence with the pro-forma journal entries provided in the MNGAS to avoid discrepancies/ differences/variances in the balances of the accounts.

We recommended that Management:
Require the Municipal Engineer’s Office (MEO) to provide the concerned offices, the designated Property and Supply Officer, Inventory Committee, and MAccO, of available records pertaining to local road networks with complete description and cost segregation to enable reconciliation of respective existing records and, prospectively, to facilitate the preparation of required reports and records in the format prescribed under COA Circular No. 2015-008;
Direct the designated Property and Supply Officer to prepare and maintain the Local Road Network Property Card for all roads and its components, including Road Map. Moreover, ensure that the Report on Local Road Network be prepared by the designated Property and Supply Officer at the end of accounting period;
Require the Inventory Committee to conduct physical count of its road networks in order to ascertain the existence of the balance of the account Road Networks;
Reconcile the reports and records of designated Property and Supply Officer and Inventory Committee with the MAccO to ensure the fair presentation of the Road Networks account in the FS; and
Adequately provide the required disclosure pertaining to Road Networks in the Notes to FS.

We reiterated our previous recommendations for the Management to:
Prepare and submit copy of the RPCPPE to the Auditor in prescribed format, not later than January 31 of each year;
Ensure that the RPCPPE reflects comprehensively and cumulatively the PPE of the LGU as of the date of the conduct of physical count;
In the preparation of the RPCPPE, strictly follow the prescribed format and ensure that the different equally significant columns are properly and completely filled out to ensure that all items are properly identified and accounted for; and
Perform periodic reconciliation of property cards to ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated, cleared and reconciled with the books of accounts.

We recommended the Management to:
Issue demand letters to:
Notify the concerned officials and employees of their responsibility to settle their unliquidated cash advance/s. If settlement was not received, withhold from their salaries considering that they have been notified and given more adequate time to liquidate;
Official/s who already ended their term and employees of Department of Education to immediately cause the liquidation or settlement of the unliquidated balances;
Request the write-off of the unliquidated cash advances of the deceased, retired or absconded employee/s following the guidelines and procedures on the write-off of dormant unliquidated cash advance in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016;
Stop the practice of granting additional cash advance to concerned officials and employees unless the previous cash advance granted to them has been liquidated;
Strictly monitor periodically the submission of liquidation reports to ensure timely accounting thereof to avoid undue accumulation of outstanding cash advances; and
Strictly comply with the provisions of the Circulars pertaining to cash advances.

We recommended that the:

a. Municipal Engineer, the official in-charge of the motor pool and the Municipal Accountant immediately submit the documents required for technical evaluation and inspection;

b. Municipal Accountant and the Municipal Budget Officer, in coordination with the Municipal Engineer, reconcile their records to determine the total cost incurred for each project;

c. Municipal Budget Officer i) provide the Audit Team with certified list of projects charged against each lump sum appropriation and their corresponding costs based on Program of Works and ii) henceforth verify the existence of specific appropriations before certifying to that effect in Box B of the Obligation Request; 

d. Municipal Accountant see to it that disbursements on infrastructure projects are supported with sufficient technical documents and that vouchers and supporting documents of completed projects are immediately submitted for audit; and

e. Municipal Mayor, as the one primarily responsible for all government funds and property of the municipal government, ensure that the required reports and documents are submitted by the concerned municipal government officials to the Audit Team in such form and within the period prescribed by the Commission pursuant to the provisions of Sections 39 and 122 of PD No. 1445.

We recommended that the:
LCE, through the Municipal Accountant, (a) serve written notices to all concerned accountable officers requiring settlement of their outstanding cash advances and institute legal action against them, if warranted; (b) ensure that all concerned officers and employees strictly comply with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 97-002 and Section 89 of P.D. No. 1445 on the grant, utilization and liquidation of cash advances; and (c) ensure that no additional CAs is granted to the Municipal Treasurer unless the purpose of grant is for official travel;
Disbursing Officers/SDOs submit liquidations of the CAs within the prescribed period provided in COA Circular No. 97-002;
Municipal Accountant:
prepare the schedule of all receivables, unliquidated cash advances, and fund transfers every quarter;
reconstruct the SLs for the cash advances to officers and employees totaling ₱4,232,037.30 as of December 31, 2019 and immediately submit the same to the Audit Team;
immediately submit the following documents relevant to the unliquidated cash advances for filing of appropriate cases against erring accountable officers (AOs):
Authenticated copy of Appointment of the AO granted cash advance;
Designation or authority to draw cash advance;
Authenticated copy of AO’s fidelity bond;
Authenticated copy of demand letter of the local chief executive and proof of receipt by the AO and answer/explanation thereto, if any;
Paid check/s for the cash advance; and
Other relevant documents
strictly monitor the grant and liquidation of cash advances to ensure that no additional cash advance is granted unless the previous one have been duly liquidated and accounted for;
ensure that all cash advances to be granted to disbursing officers/SDOs are supported with complete documentation in accordance with Item 1.1 of COA Circular No. 97-002; and
record the CAs for official travel to Advances to Officers and Employees account in accordance with the Revised Chart of Accounts prescribed by COA Circular No. 2015-009.
LCE and the Municipal Accountant, in all instances, ensure that each provisions of COA Circular No. 97-002 are strictly observed and that all cash advances are fully liquidated at the end of the year.

We recommended that the:
Inventory Committee (i) immediately complete the physical inventory of all municipal property; (ii) prepare the Report on the Physical Count of PPE and Report on the Physical Count of the Local Road Network System to be reconciled with the Property Cards, PPE Ledger Cards, Road Network Ledger Cards and other accounting records; and (iii) submit a copy thereof to the Audit Team;
Municipal Accountant (i) reconcile the material differences of total acquisition costs of PPE account balances reported in year-end financial statements with the lapsing schedules; (ii) reconstruct and complete the PPE ledger cards and recompute for the correct accumulated depreciation of all PPE particularly the local road network account;
GSO maintain complete property cards with complete information to be reconciled with ARE and accounting records; and
Municipal Engineer (i) submit a complete report on the costs, description and specifications and cost segregation of the road components; and (ii) regularly assess each road component for impairment.

We recommended that the:
Local Chief Executive:
re-evaluate, thru Human Resource Management Officer, the existing contracts of services that need to be converted to contractual or casual appointment and ensure that the contracts or appointments contain the position titles and salary grade allocation patterned to the Compensation and Position Classification System and DBM Budget Circular No. 2018-4 for uniformity and consistency of salary rates;
strictly comply with the provisions of Section 133 of 2017 ORAOHRA that no individual COS employees shall be made to perform functions pertaining to regular positions nor be designated to positions exercising control or supervision over regular and career employees;
ensure that the hiring of individual COS, which require adequate external technical and professional capability and expertise that are beyond the existing capacity of the regular staff of the Municipality, be subjected to the rules and regulations on the procurement of consulting services under the 2016 Revised I.R.R. of R.A. No. 9184;
specify in the contract/appointment the duties and functions of the contractual and casual employees and explicitly provide in the Contract of Service the detailed scope of work, expected output/deliverables, time frame or delivery schedules, minimum qualifications, payment terms and other provisions necessary in the interest of the Municipality; and
limit only to regular/permanent employees the benefit of attending seminars and tranings chargeable against local funds;
Municipal Accountant review the completeness and propriety of supporting documents attached to the payrolls/DVs covering payment of salaries/wages of COS/JO personnel to ensure compliance with pertinent rules and regulations and the regularity of their claims before processing them for payment; and
Disbursing Officer release payment of salaries/wages or any money due the casual/contractual/COS/JO personnel directly to them and to allow Special Power of Attorneys in lieu of personal appearance only in exceptional cases.

We recommended to the Municipal Mayor and the E-Trike Officer the following:
Enter into a Contract Agreement with the Prospective New Owners (PNOs), taking into consideration the requirements laid down in Item IV of the Deployment Plan;
Adhere to the value of the E-trikes based on the Property Transfer Report of USD10,249.00 or ₱533,224.72 at the time of its turnover to the Municipality;
Compel the PNOs to complete the requirements enumerated in Appendix C of the Deployment Plan to erase any doubt on the regularity of their selection;
Register the E-trikes with the Land Transportation Office under the name of the Municipality to easily facilitate the transfer of ownership to the PNOs;
Construct the four charging stations with sufficient number of socket outlets  in accordance with the proposal in the Deployment Plan and designate;
Assign a charging station manager or attendant who will oversee the operation and safety of the charging stations;
Ensure that all collections related to E-trike Program are collected under the Municipal Treasurer’s Office and are duly acknowledged with the issuance of official receipts;
Collect from the PNOs the charging fees and applicable penalties in case of delayed payments in accordance with Items IV(A) and IV(C) of the Deployment Plan;
Ensure that all properties received thru donation are properly inspected and accepted by the General Services Office and that the copy of Deed of Donation and other pertinent documents are submitted immediately to the Accounting Office for proper recording in the books;
Submit the document evidencing authority granted by the DOE to the LGU to utilize the five units of E-trike for official use of the Municipality and work for the immediate deployment of the remaining E-trike units; and
Notify DOE in writing of any non-compliance of the terms as provided for in the Deployment Plan and Deed of Donation, submit justification and request for approval of any necessary changes that should be implemented in the E-trike project.

We recommended that the:
a. LCE (i) reevaluate, through the Municipal Engineer and MPDC, the number of infrastructure projects which were identified to be undertaken “by administration” and assess whether the Municipality’s limited manpower as well as the technical capability to undertake is sufficient to allow project implementation and completion within the time schedule; (ii) weigh the advantages and disadvantages of a “by administration” scheme and straight contracting and thereafter consider which is better without sacrificing the timely delivery of basic services and facilities needed by the public; (iii) issue termination of contract to erring contractor who has negative slippage of ten percent (10%) or more in the completion of the work pursuant to Section III-A(2) of the Guidelines on Termination of Contracts; and (iv) cause the forfeiture of their performance security pursuant to Section 8.5 of the R-IRR of R.A. No. 9184;
b. Municipal Engineer and the MPDC (i) reevaluate and complete the list of infrastructure projects in the monitoring report and provide all the minimum required information on the implementation of each project; and (ii) immediately submit to the Audit Team the consolidated status report/information of all the infrastructure projects started, completed and still on-going as of December 31, 2019;
c. Municipal Engineer (a) hasten the implementation of the infrastructure projects and make sure that all projects are strictly monitored and implemented in accordance with plans and schedules; (b) ensure that the POWs contain information on when to start the project and number of days to complete the project; and (c) immediately submit the documents required for technical evaluation and inspection;
d. LCE, ME and MPDC strictly comply with the guidelines of COA Circular No. 2013-004 regarding information and publicity of PPAs;
e. Municipal Budget Officer provide the Audit Team with the certified list of projects charged against each lump sum appropriation and their corresponding costs based on the POWs and submit the copies of registries for continuing appropriations of CY 2018 and below; and
f. Municipal Accountant and ME compute and impose liquidated damages against the contractor of Construction of Banuangin Falls Water System which was completed beyond contract expiry date pursuant to Section 8 of the Contract Implementation Guidelines for the Procurement of Infrastructure Projects.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Accounting Unit and Property/Supplies Unit:

Prioritize the conduct of physical count of all the LGU’s PPE;




Prepare and submit copy of the RPCPPE to the Auditor in prescribed format, not later than January 31 of each year. In the preparation of the report, the different column should be properly fill-up to ensure that all items are properly identified and accounted for; 
Perform periodic reconciliation of property cards to ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated, cleared and reconciled with the books of accounts; and




Maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards and property cards, for each class of PPE listing therein the data as to its acquisition, description, custody, estimated life, rate of depreciation, disposal, and other information about the property, plant and equipment, based on the source documents of the transactions.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Strictly adhere to the above-cited laws, rules and regulations;

Instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant to immediately submit the subject 37 DVs together with its complete supporting documents to avoid suspensions in post audit;

Instruct the OIC-Municipal Treasurer to ensure that paid DVs are intact as listed in the RCI upon transmittal to the Office of the Accountant; and

Instruct the Municipal Accountant to always transmit complete submission of accounts to facilitate thorough audit and verification of the agency’s financial transactions.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of actions: 
Enforce the settlement of previously drawn cash advances under the prescribed period of settlement as provided under existing rules and regulations, otherwise, stop granting additional cash advance to personnel with outstanding cash advance;
Exert extra efforts to recover outstanding cash advances from Accountable Officers who are no longer in the service nor connected with the Municipality;

Direct the Municipal Accountant to send demand letters to the concerned Accountable Officers with outstanding unliquidated cash advances; and
Institute the appropriate legal actions/sanctions against those erring Accountable Officers/employees for continued non-compliance with the existing laws, rules and regulations on the granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances, if warranted.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Optimize the utilization of the 20 per cent LDF and implement the PPAs within the timelines in order to achieve the socio-economic and environmental outcomes, essential in the attainment of its goals and objectives of a desired quality of life for its constituents;

Consider the equitable distribution of PPAs listed among the three important aspects of sector development mandated under DILG/DBM JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 and previous issuances as well as the requirements of Sections 16 and 17 of the Local Government Code (LGC) of 1991, in order to cater not only the social development needs of the constituents but also the economic development and environmental management PPAs which will directly address the actual needs of the intended beneficiaries; 
Adopt a well-defined strategy in order to enhance the present monitoring and review activities during the planning, procurement, contract implementation and program evaluation phase, in order for the planners, implementers as well as evaluators to continuously monitor the timely implementation, so that immediate appropriate and corrective actions could be done on noted gaps along the way; and
For the meantime that there are no additional plantilla items, Management should hire additional Engineers and/or Architects on a JO or Contractual basis to augment the existing personnel in the MEO.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that the Gender and Development (GAD) Focal Point System (GFPS) is in place, fully functional and that the members have the capacity and influence to promote gender mainstreaming that will promote efficient planning, implementation and monitoring of GAD activities;
Follow the Calendar Schedule for the preparation of GPB for LGUs and incorporate the DILG-approved/endorsed GPB in the Annual Budget to ensure that the programs, projects and activities reflected thereat are in accordance with the existing regulations and guidelines;
Submit annual GAD Accomplishment Report accompanied by the required documents specified in the above-cited provisions;
With collaboration with the SB, formulate a GAD Code and implement it within the LGU and its barangays; and
Follow PCW-DILG-DBM-NEDA JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by JMC No. 2016-01 to fully address and implement applicable provisions in the convention on the elimination of all forms of discrimination against women and promote gender equality within the municipality.

We therefore recommended the following courses of action:

Accomplish and submit immediately the deficiencies noted in the disbursement of government funds;


Ensure that claims against government funds are covered with duly approved vouchers and supported with complete documents before payment of the same;

The Municipal Accountant should not process transactions that are not properly supported with the required documents;

Advise other concerned officials not to approve and disburse the funds of the government without satisfying the requirements set by rules and regulations; and

Strictly enforce the rules enunciated in COA Circular No.2012-001, Sections 4(6) and 61 of P.D. No. 1445 before payment of claims.

We therefore recommended that Municipal Treasurer:

Update the cashbook daily based on the Report of Collections and Deposits;

Closely monitor cash balances by reconciling daily the cash on hand with the cash balance in the cashbook to ensure the accuracy and physical existence of cash on hand;
Reconcile the cashbook balances with the accounting records every end of the month. Take up immediately the necessary corrections should there be a difference between these two records; and
Accomplish certification as to the correctness and completeness of the recorded transactions at month-end after the last entry in the cashbook.

