We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:
Optimize the utilization of the 20 per cent LDF and implement the PAPs within the timelines in order to achieve the socio-economic and environmental outcomes, essential in the attainment of its goals and objectives of a desired quality of life for its constituents;
Consider the equitable distribution of PPAs listed among the three important aspects of sector development mandated under DILG/DBM JMC No. 2017-1 dated February 22, 2017 and previous issuances as well as the requirements of Sections 16 and 17 of the LGC of 1991, in order to cater not only the social development needs of the constituents but also the economic development and environmental management PPAs which will directly address the actual needs of the intended beneficiaries;
Adopt a well-defined strategy in order to enhance the present monitoring and review activities during the planning, procurement, contract implementation and program evaluation phase, in order for the planners, implementers as well as evaluators to continuously monitor the timely implementation, so that immediate appropriate and corrective actions could be done on noted gaps along the way; and
For the meantime that there are no additional plantilla items, Management should hire additional Engineers and/or Architects on a Job Order or Contractual basis to augment the existing personnel in the Municipal Engineers Office.

We reiterated our previous recommendations that the Accounting Unit and Property/Supplies Unit:

Prioritize the conduct of physical count of all the LGU’s PPE; 



Prepare and submit copy of the RPCPPE to the Auditor in prescribed format, not later than January 31 of each year. In the preparation of the report, the different column should be properly fill-up to ensure that all items are properly identified and accounted for; 


Perform periodic reconciliation of property cards to ensure that all discrepancies are immediately investigated, cleared and reconciled with the books of accounts; and


Maintain complete and updated PPE Ledger Cards and property cards, for each class of PPE listing therein the data as to its acquisition, description, custody, estimated life, rate of depreciation, disposal, and other information about the property, plant and equipment, based on the source documents of the transactions.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Prioritize the preparation and submission of the Monthly BRS to ascertain the reconciling items pertaining to the difference amounting to ₱33,388.00 in order to establish the correct balances of the Cash in Bank accounts for all funds as required in Section 74 of P.D. No. 1445 and Section 3.2 of COA Circular No. 96-011 dated October 2, 1996; 

Necessary adjustments, if any, should be affected to avoid accumulation thereof and to present the correct balance of the cash in bank accounts in the financial statements; 

Prepare subsidiary ledgers for the cash accounts of the Municipality;

Regularly monitor its bank accounts to avoid occurrence of inactive/dormant account; and

Coordinate with the Landbank of the Philippines (LBP) on the proper handling of cash balance in the dormant Current Account No. 0412-1066-87.

We recommended that Management take the following courses of action:

Transfer all the unexpended QRF and Mitigation Fund (MF)-MOOE to a Special Trust Fund while all unobligated balance of LDRRMF for Capital Outlay (CO) should be made continuing in the GF until the projects funded therefore are completed in accordance with the accounting and reporting guidelines provided under COA Circular No. 2012-002;




Submit a revised Annual Investment Plan (AIP) as approved by the local sanggunian and LCE upon recommendation of the Local Disaster Risk Reduction and Management  Council (LDRRMC) in accordance with the approved Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Plan (LDRRMP) for the release and utilization of the unexpended balances of Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Fund (LDRRMF);

Observe strictly the requirement set forth under COA Circular No. 2012-002 specifically Section 5.1.16 on the proper and adequate disclosure/discussion in the Notes to the FS of the amounts and details of the unexpended balance of LDRRMF; and 

Prepare and certify the correctness of the Report on the Sources and Utilization of DRRMF and the LDRRM Officer and submit the same to the identified offices on or before the 15th day after the end of each month. Also, the LDRRM Officer should comply with the posting requirements of such reports in conspicuous places including websites, if any, of the LGU/LDRRMO.

We recommended that Management:

Enforce the proper granting, utilization and liquidation of cash advances by requiring the Accounting Office to strictly implement the rules and regulations prescribed under Section 89 of P.D. No. 1445 and COA Circular No. 97-002;

Require all concerned officials and employees to liquidate immediately their cash advances;

Inability to liquidate after the issuance of another demand, suspend the salaries of erring officials and employees, or cause the filing and institution of appropriate charges for failure to liquidate the cash advances, pursuant to the same regulations; and

Exert effort to cause the liquidation of the cash advances of personnel who were no longer in the service, otherwise those officers/employees who issued clearance shall be held personally liable, including the Accountant who failed to faithfully comply with his duty to monitor the liquidation of cash advances.

We recommended that Management:

Ensure that the Gender and Development (GAD) Focal Point System (GFPS) is in place, fully functional and that the members have the capacity and influence to promote gender mainstreaming that will promote efficient planning, implementation and monitoring of GAD activities;

Follow the Calendar Schedule for the preparation of GAD Plan and Budget (GPB) for LGUs and incorporate the DILG-approved/endorsed GPB in the Annual Budget to ensure that the programs, projects and activities reflected thereat are in accordance with the existing regulations and guidelines;

Submit annual GAD Accomplishment Report accompanied by the required documents specified in the above-cited provisions;

Set-up and maintain GAD database as spearheaded by the Local Planning and Development Office that will serve as basis for gender-responsive planning, programming and policy formulation;

With collaboration with the SB, formulate a GAD Code and implement it within the LGU and its barangays; and 

Follow Philippine Commission on Women (PCW), DILG, DBM, National Economic and Development Authority (NEDA) JMC No. 2013-01, as amended by JMC No. 2016-01 to fully address and implement applicable provisions in the convention on the elimination of all forms of discrimination against women and promote gender equality within the municipality.

We recommended that Management:

Give priority in the establishment of fully functioning Municipal and SWM Board that will monitor and ensure the effective implementation of the solid waste management plan and programs;

Hasten the acquisition of suitable land for SWM Facility. Make it so that the Municipality aims not only to construct a control dumpsite which was also prohibited after five years in the enactment of R.A. No. 9003, but a sanitary landfill which was required by the same law;

Submit a certification from the Department of Environment and Natural Resources (DENR), authorizing the type of dump site which the municipality can use; and

Fully implement the provisions of R.A. No. 9003 for the optimum management of the Municipality′s solid waste.

We therefore recommended the following courses of action:

Accomplish and submit immediately the deficiencies noted in the disbursement of government funds;

Ensure that claims against government funds are covered with duly approved vouchers and supported with complete documents before payment of the same;

The Municipal Accountant should not process transactions that are not properly supported with the required documents;

Advise other concerned officials not to approve and disburse the funds of the government without satisfying the requirements set by rules and regulations; and

Strictly enforce the rules enunciated in COA Circular No.2012-001, Sections 4(6) and 61 of P.D. No. 1445 before payment of claims.

We therefore recommended that Municipal Treasurer:

Update the cashbook daily based on the Report of Collections and Deposits;

Closely monitor cash balances by reconciling daily the cash on hand with the cash balance in the cashbook to ensure the accuracy and physical existence of cash on hand;

Reconcile the cashbook balances with the accounting records every end of the month. Take up immediately the necessary corrections should there be a difference between these two records; and

Accomplish certification as to the correctness and completeness of the recorded transactions at month-end after the last entry in the cashbook.

We recommended that Management:

Comply strictly with the pertinent provisions of CSC Memorandum Circular No. 40, series of 1998, as amended regarding the hiring of job orders;

Ensure compliance with CSC laws, rules and regulations in the preparation of contract of services or job orders. Job order contract should contain the specific duties and responsibilities in order to match their skills against the work to be performed;

Instruct the Human Resource Management Officer (HRMO) to strengthen the internal control system in hiring additional workforce through job orders; and

Require the Municipal Accountant to strictly observe laws, rules and regulations particularly as to completeness of documentary requirements before payment of wages of JOs pursuant to COA Circular No. 2012-001.

We recommended that the Agency:

Require the drivers to accomplish the DTTs for every trip undertaken as required;

Prepare and submit Monthly Report of Official Travels per vehicle summarizing in chronological order the trips for the month;

Submit the Monthly Report of Fuel Consumption to the Auditor for verification. The report shall show among others, the type of motor vehicles used during the month total distance travelled, total fuel used and the normal fuel consumption for each vehicle.
